      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The practical consequences for the end user go far beyond just a slightly less clean feel; it's a systemic degradation of the linen's performance. If the weave integrity breaks down, the fabric starts to fail in multiple ways, not just by letting in dust.\n\nFirst, the structural integrity suffers, leading to premature wear—those weak spots become stress points where the fabric is more likely to snag, tear, or develop permanent creases. Second, the barrier function failure means moisture management is compromised; if the weave is too open, it might wick moisture poorly or, conversely, allow excessive moisture to penetrate and hold onto it, leading to mildew or mustiness.\n\nIn short, a compromised weave means the linen doesn't perform its intended function as a durable, high-quality textile. It starts to behave like a cheap, loosely woven rag, even if the Egyptian cotton fibers themselves are magnificent. It's the difference between a well-built fortress and a collection of scattered, easily breached sandcastles.",
